<TITLE> North Korea's Kim holds rare meeting with China envoy </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SEOUL, Jan 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Reclusive North Korean leader Kim Jong-il held a rare meeting with a visiting Chinese communist party official on Wednesday, just days ahead of a fresh US push to move a stalled nuclear disarmament deal forward. North Korea's KCNA news agency said Kim held talks with the Chinese communist party's head of international liaison, Wang Jiarui, and his delegates and received a message from Chinese President Hu Jintao. KCNA said Kim and the guests had lunch, and discussions were held in an amicable mood, but did not give further details. The meeting comes as a US diplomat, Sung Kim, heads to Pyongyang on Thursday to try to push forward a deal to end the North's nuclear arms programme in return for massive aid and better diplomatic standing. Sung Kim said on Tuesday that the North must give a complete account of its nuclear arms programme, dismissing a report that Washington was willing to accept less to begin taking it off a terrorism blacklist and easing trade restrictions. North Korea began taking apart its Yongbyon nuclear plant in November as called for in the six-country disarmament deal but has missed an end-2007 deadline to release a list of its fissile material and nuclear weapons. It has also failed to answer US suspicions of enriching uranium for weapons. Wang's trip was part of a normal exchange, the Chinese foreign ministry has said. Sung Kim said on arriving in South Korea on Tuesday that he had no plans to meet with Wa
